A week ago I published an introduction to Umbral, a batteries-included web framework for Rust. That post described the shape of the thing. This one is the opposite; no philosophy, just a keyboard. We are going to build a small task tracker and turn every switch on, one at a time, so that by the end you have run the commands yourself and seen each surface come up.
Read full blog here
Here is the promise, stated plainly so you can hold me to it - we will write our data model exactly once, in one file, and then every other surface - the database schema, the query API, the admin, the REST endpoints, their documentation, an interactive API console, and a GraphQL endpoint will be built from that one declaration. You will not re-type a field name. You will not describe the schema to REST and then describe it again to GraphQL.
If you have used Django or Rails, the workflow will feel familiar. The difference is that it is Rust the whole way down. A nullable column is an Option<T>, a fallible call returns a Result, and the plugin you write to hold your models is structurally identical to the built-in ones.
Two honest caveats up front. Umbral is pre-1.0 and published on crates.io, so the exact APIs still move between releases. Treat the code here as the current shape (Umbral v0.0.10), not a frozen contract. And this is a beginner-friendly walkthrough. It favors showing you every step over showing you every option.
Step 1: Create the project
Install the CLI and scaffold a project
cargo install umbral-cliumbral startproject tracker
cd trackerstartproject gives you a runnable app. Start it
cargo run -- devcargo run -- <command> is how you drive the app - the generated main.rs builds your App and hands it to Umbral's CLI dispatcher, so dev, migrate, makemigrations, and createsuperuser all flow through the same binary. Open http://127.0.0.1:8000/ and you have a rendered page and an admin login before writing a line of your own code.
Now create yourself an admin user (in a second terminal, leave dev running)
cargo run -- createsuperuserStep 2: Create an app to hold your models
In Umbral, a feature area lives in a plugin — its own small crate. Auth is a plugin, the admin is a plugin, and your code is a plugin too. That is the one idea the framework is built around. Your app is not a special case, it is a plugin like every other. You create one with startapp.
umbral startapp projectsThis scaffolds plugins/projects/, a self-contained crate, and wires it into your project's Cargo.toml for you. Inside you get the following.
plugins/projects/
src/
lib.rs # the Plugin impl: registers models, routes, lifecycle hooks
models.rs # your #[derive(Model)] structs go here
views.rs # HTTP handlers (we won't need custom ones today)
urls.rs # this app's URL routesThe generated src/lib.rs is the important one. It defines a plugin struct and an empty Plugin implementation, the contract every plugin fills in.
// plugins/projects/src/lib.rs - as generatedpub mod models;
use umbral::migrate::ModelMeta;
use umbral::plugin::{AppContext, Plugin, PluginError};
use umbral::web::Router;
#[derive(Debug, Default, Clone)]
pub struct ProjectsPlugin;
impl Plugin for ProjectsPlugin {
fn name(&self) -> &'static str {
"projects"
}
fn models(&self) -> Vec<ModelMeta> {
// Register every model this plugin owns so makemigrations
// picks it up. We'll fill this in next.
Vec::new()
}
fn routes(&self) -> Router {
urls::router()
}
fn on_ready(&self, _ctx: &AppContext) -> Result<(), PluginError> {
Ok(())
}
}
Keep that models() method in mind - it is where our schema gets connected to the rest of the framework. We come back to it in Step 4.
Step 3: Declare the schema, once
Open plugins/projects/src/models.rs and write the whole data model. This is the only place we describe our tables. Read it closely, because every later step is this same declaration wearing a different hat.
Learn more about models here
Learn more about model fields / column types here
// plugins/projects/src/models.rsuse chrono::{DateTime, Utc};
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
use umbral::prelude::*;
use umbral_auth::AuthUser;
// A small, closed set of states. `Choices` teaches the framework the
// allowed values, so the admin renders a dropdown, the OpenAPI schema
// lists an enum, and GraphQL gets an enum type - all from this one place.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Serialize, Deserialize, Choices)]
#[choices(rename_all = "snake_case")]
#[serde(rename_all = "snake_case")]
pub enum TaskStatus {
Todo,
InProgress,
Blocked,
Done,
}
#[derive(Debug, Clone, sqlx::FromRow, Serialize, Deserialize, Model)]
pub struct Project {
pub id: i64,
#[umbral(unique)]
pub slug: String,
#[umbral(string)]
pub name: String,
pub description: Option<String>,
#[umbral(default = "false")]
pub is_archived: bool,
#[umbral(auto_now_add)]
pub created_at: DateTime<Utc>,
}
#[derive(Debug, Clone, sqlx::FromRow, Serialize, Deserialize, Model)]
pub struct Label {
pub id: i64,
#[umbral(unique, string)]
pub name: String,
#[umbral(default = "#888888")]
pub color: String,
}
#[derive(Debug, Clone, sqlx::FromRow, Serialize, Deserialize, Model)]
pub struct Task {
pub id: i64,
#[umbral(string)]
pub title: String,
pub description: Option<String>,
#[umbral(choices)]
pub status: TaskStatus,
// A required FK: every task belongs to a project.
pub project: ForeignKey<Project>,
// An optional FK: a task may be unassigned. Nullable in the DB,
// and therefore `Option<...>` in Rust. The type carries the nullability.
pub assignee: Option<ForeignKey<AuthUser>>,
// Many-to-many. The framework creates a `task_labels` junction table
// at migration time; you never hand-write it.
#[sqlx(skip)]
#[serde(skip)]
pub labels: M2M<Label>,
pub due_date: Option<DateTime<Utc>>,
#[umbral(auto_now_add)]
pub created_at: DateTime<Utc>,
#[umbral(auto_now)]
pub updated_at: DateTime<Utc>,
}
#[derive(Debug, Clone, sqlx::FromRow, Serialize, Deserialize, Model)]
pub struct Comment {
pub id: i64,
pub task: ForeignKey<Task>,
pub author: ForeignKey<AuthUser>,
pub body: String,
#[umbral(auto_now_add)]
pub created_at: DateTime<Utc>,
}
There is one dependency to add before this compiles. Because assignee and author point at the built-in user model, the projects plugin needs the auth crate. Add it to plugins/projects/Cargo.toml.
[dependencies]
umbral-auth = "0.0.10" # for ForeignKey<AuthUser>Four things in the models are the whole idea, so it is worth slowing down.

• Nullability lives in the type. assignee: Option<ForeignKey<AuthUser>> is a nullable column and an optional Rust value at once. There is no second place where "this can be null" is recorded and could drift out of sync.

• ForeignKey<Project> is a relationship, not just an integer. The framework knows Task points at Project. That single fact is what later lets GraphQL resolve task { project { name } } without you declaring that edge anywhere.

• M2M<Label> is a whole junction table you did not write. No migration boilerplate, no join model.

• Choices on the enum is a promise about the allowed values that every read and write surface will honour.
Step 4: Register the models with your plugin
Declaring a struct is not enough — the framework has to know it exists. That is what the models() method on your plugin is for. Go back to plugins/projects/src/lib.rs and fill it in.
// plugins/projects/src/lib.rsfn models(&self) -> Vec<ModelMeta> {
vec![
ModelMeta::for_::<models::Project>(),
ModelMeta::for_::<models::Label>(),
ModelMeta::for_::<models::Task>(),
ModelMeta::for_::<models::Comment>(),
]
}
ModelMeta::for_::<T>() hands the migration engine everything it learned from your #[derive(Model)]. That means the columns, their types and nullability, the foreign keys, the many-to-many, and the choices. This is the connective tissue. Every surface downstream reads from these registrations, not from your structs directly. (ModelMeta needs to be in scope - the generated lib.rs refers to it as the fully-qualified umbral::migrate::ModelMeta; add use umbral::migrate::ModelMeta; at the top if you want the short form shown here.)
Step 5: Wire the plugin into the app
Now open the project’s src/main.rs and register ProjectsPlugin on the app builder, alongside the built-in plugins. This is the control room - the one place where you say which batteries are installed. Here is the whole thing.
// src/main.rsuse umbral::prelude::*; // brings the `Model` trait into scope for `table_name()`
use umbral_admin::{AdminModel, AdminPlugin};
use umbral_auth::{AuthPlugin, AuthUser, BearerAuthentication};
use umbral_graphql::GraphqlPlugin;
use umbral_openapi::OpenApiPlugin;
use umbral_playground::PlaygroundPlugin;
use umbral_rest::{IsAuthenticated, PageNumberPagination, ResourceConfig, RestPlugin};
use umbral_security::{SecurityConfig, SecurityPlugin};
use umbral_sessions::SessionsPlugin;
// Your app's models, so the registrations below can name them by
// `Project::table_name()` instead of a hardcoded string.
use projects::models::{Comment, Label, Project, Task};
#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error + Send + Sync>> {
// Install the tracing subscriber (this line is in the generated main.rs -
// keep it). `App::serve` logs "umbral serving on ..." through `tracing`, so
// without a subscriber the server binds and serves SILENTLY and looks hung.
let _log = umbral_logs::observability::init(umbral_logs::ObservabilityConfig::from_env());
let settings = Settings::from_env()?;
let pool = umbral::db::connect(&settings.database_url).await?;
let app = App::builder()
.settings(settings)
.database("default", pool)
// --- Built-in plugins -------------------------------------------
.plugin(AuthPlugin::<AuthUser>::default().with_default_routes())
.plugin(SessionsPlugin::default())
// --- Your app ---------------------------------------------------
.plugin(projects::ProjectsPlugin::default())
// (admin, REST, OpenAPI, playground, GraphQL get added
// in the steps below - one plugin each.)
// `build_deferred`, not `build`: it wires up pools and the model
// registry but holds each plugin's `on_ready` hook until `dispatch`
// has read argv - so a management command like `makemigrations`
// runs before the hooks fire. This is what `startproject` generates.
.build_deferred()?;
umbral_cli::dispatch(app).await
}
That .plugin(projects::ProjectsPlugin::default()) line is the answer to "how do I turn my app on." startapp even prints the exact line to paste. Everything from here is adding one more .plugin(...) to this builder and watching a new surface appear over the same four models.
Step 6: Migrate
Umbral autodetects the difference between your registered models and the last applied migration, then writes the migration file for you.
cargo run -- makemigrations
cargo run -- migratemakemigrations diffs your models against the recorded snapshot and emits an ordered, reversible migration. It creates the project, label, task, and comment tables, plus the task_labels junction, with the foreign keys ordered so they apply cleanly. migrate runs whatever has not been applied yet and records it in a tracking table.
This is the everyday loop, and it is not a one-time thing — change a field, run the two commands again, and you get an ALTER. One rule the framework takes seriously. Your existing rows are the test, not an obstacle. Add a NOT NULL column with no default to a populated table and the migration is supposed to fail loudly and make you supply the backfill value. That failure is the feature. Wiping the database to get a clean run just hides the bug you would have hit in production.
Step 7: Query it with the typed ORM
The tables exist; now query them from Rust. The ORM gives you a typed query surface that compiles down to parameterized SQL.
